Perspectives on Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations unsettled large parts of Asia.
A year ago, U.S. President Donald Trump returned from his particularly elaborate "State Visit Plus" to Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-Chinese campaign rhetoric would finally become a thing of the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are entangled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the U.S. "strategic engagement" in China with "strategic competition."
Adding to this is the fact that the U.S., European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
Today, there is great uncertainty in financial markets, while growth is slowing in China and Europe, and in America, the higher interest rates are starting to take effect.
The uncertainty about the future development of nuclear talks with North Korea also dims the picture.
What are therefore the prospects for U.S.-China relations in 2019?
It is likely that there will be an agreement on the reduction of the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions China will make by March.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the targeted timeframe.
If tariffs were negotiated one after another, a year could pass.
If Chinese economic reformers, however, adopt a more drastic approach by gradually committing to the abolition of all tariffs and urging Americans to follow suit, a quicker outcome could result.
That would however go against Chinese trade officials, who have been trained for decades to give little, let alone everything, all at once.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively straightforward.
Nevertheless, reform is something different from the way contractual agreements might be interpreted in practice, even if there should be no specific provisions on technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property is however extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made under the administration of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed again.
Their enforcement or the judicial action in cases of infringement on intellectual property remains a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism would be to subject relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international arbitration institutions based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically entrusted with the enforcement of intellectual property protection.
If China raises objections, it could develop its own international arbitration procedure based in China.
For that, China would have to appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration panel in order to strengthen its international credibility.
No one trusts Chinese trade courts.
To meet its own domestic reform needs, China must move toward completely independent trade and civil chambers within its judicial system, even though the criminal chamber continues to be subject to political control.
The U.S. concerns regarding state subsidies under China's "Made in China 2025" strategy are unlikely to be easily resolved.
It is a fact that all countries provide a degree of state support to their domestic technology sectors, even though this is highest in China.
Even if we prescribed the maximum level of state support for a particular company, it would be difficult to assess compliance.
I am not confident that there will be an agreement in this area.
Perhaps America must simply outmaneuver China by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China may offer tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
So could China, over time, decide to take the drastic step of agreeing on tariff-free trade not only with the U.S., but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
In this way, China would have a nearly irresistible opportunity to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to curb the trend toward protectionism.
In the course of such a shift, China might request membership from the member states of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) in order to outpace the U.S. (which had exited the free trade agreement as one of Trump's first official actions) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably agile when it discovers a political opening and market opportunity.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations regarding China's accession to the TPP have decreased since the recent visit of Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in its relations with the U.S., China is likely to be committed in its general foreign and security policy in 2019 to resolving conflicts in its relations with other countries.
There is already a certain normalization in relations with Japan.
Recent data from Japan's Coast Guard indicates a significant reduction in Chinese incursions into the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands area in the East China Sea.
Also the tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea, China aims to reduce through the accelerated negotiation of a "Code of Conduct."
In addition, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India after the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could begin to moderate its stance toward Taiwan, in light of the electoral defeat suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party, which supports Taiwan's independence, in the local and regional elections last month.
This would naturally change radically if the U.S. continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Further incidents at sea with the U.S. in the South China Sea are occurring, and the conflict could escalate if the U.S. more clearly emphasizes its stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
China will continue to implement its major project "New Silk Road" across all of Eurasia.
However, the initiative in China has generated less political fervor in recent months.
Among Chinese officials, discussions have already begun regarding the revision of certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota Port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns about the long-term financial viability of the New Silk Road.
In 2019, triumphant reports on the New Silk Road are therefore likely to be less frequent.
In addition, China is likely to consolidate and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than emphasize new institutions of international political action.
It is likely to continue appearing as a new defender of the WHO and maintain its stance on climate change, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
Cautious representatives of China's foreign policy establishment consider it better to focus on the existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, particularly when the U.S. consistently shows disregard for them.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the U.S. and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership is likely to use the year 2019 to form a well-informed judgment about the future of U.S. policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his administration, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new U.S. strategy in any way.
Although they have already come to the conclusion that the U.S. stance toward China has undergone a fundamental change, they remain uncertain about the exact form this change will take and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is warranted.
